The Brutal Murder of Jenny Lee

The Room

The room is cubical in shape. The floor, walls, and ceiling are identical in color and texture so that you can barely make out the edges. Light seems to come from everywhere and nowhere at the same time; there are no shadows to be seen. Before you is a lone table. Behind you is a door.

You can see a table (on which there is a key) and a door.

Hey you! Keep it down! Excessive noise is forbidden during recreational hour!

Are you awake? Nod your head if you can hear me. Good. Now, listen closely. We've got a lot to do, and so little time.

Well, go on then. Take a look around. I don't need to teach you how to look, do I? I do? You would expect, at this price point . . . Whatever. I don't have time for this. Type "help" to learn about the basic commands.
> take key

> take key
You pick up the key. Its texture feels metallic but it is oddly light.
> open door

> open door
The key slides smoothly into the keyhole. The door swings open on silent hinges.

I wouldn't look so smug if I were you. Even one of my kindergarteners could have done that. Okay, let's try something else. Something that requires a little bit of thinking . . . outside the box. Here it is. Pay attention. Take the door, and open the key.
> take door

> take door
You slide your hands along the wall and find a groove running under the frame of the door. You grasp the edges and it comes loose in your hands, falling to the floor with a soft thud. The doorway opens into the south and through it you can see another room.
