> open key

> open key
You examine the key, moving your fingers carefully around the surface. You discover a tiny pair of hinges along the side, almost invisible to the eye. You use your nails for leverage and the key cracks open. Inside is a tiny piece of paper, rolled up and sitting snugly in the hollow space. You pick it out and begin to unfurl it . . .

Not bad. Here, let me take that, thank you very much. It looks like you might be up for the job after all; you're already better than the last one. The world is not always what it seems. Keys are not always just keys. If only the police had known that . . .

I think you're ready to move on. Your task is to investigate a murder that took place seventeen years ago. I'm going to send you back to the places she used to frequent the most, so you can start looking for clues. Ready? This might be a bit disorienting, so close your eyes.

Band Room

The room is dark and spacious. A tall podium sits surrounded by a semicircle of black chairs and empty stands. Behind the podium is an elevated platform and a swivel chair; sitting here, one has a clear view of large windows blocked in by stolid evergreens. The window on the rightmost side is boarded up. On the left of the room are an old Yamaha piano and a dirty drumset. On the right side, a bookshelf runs wall-to-wall, with trophies stacked on top in ascending height. An unremarkable doorway leads to a storage area.

You can see a piano, a drum set, a podium (on which there is a binder and a book), a bookshelf, a chalkboard and a bulletin board.
You can go east.
> look at binder

> look at binder
The binder is thick but color-coded tabs tell you exactly where everything is. It's flipped open to an attendance sheet. You examine it carefully: most students have one or two absences and a couple of lates. Two people have perfect records: Colin Yates and Rebecca DeVries. Angela Zhao hasn't been to class for two weeks. Something is scrawled into the margins in blue pen:

"Note to Substitute: If Angela comes to class, her backpack is in the cabinet. The combination is set to the year the school was founded."
> look at bulletin board

> look at bulletin board
The bulletin is a battleground of broken pins and twisted staples, still stubbornly holding on to pieces of ripped paper.
Pinned to the center of the board is  a bulletin notice.
> look at bulletin notice

> look at bulletin notice
It reads:

Pickton High 50th Anniversary Talent Palooza
Friday May 9th
All Students & Members of the Community Welcome || Students $8 || Adults $15

The Vanishing Act: A Magic Show ft. Colin Yates
My Mother's Garden: Slam Poetry ft Isabella Reed
Jazz Ensemble ft Angela Zhao, Nick Gates, and Jenny Lee

And Others! Tickets Go On Sale Monday April. 28th In The Foyer. Don't Miss This Amazing Chance!

She was killed on the 8th. I never got to see her perform. She was bashed on the head with her own saxophone, the force so excessive that all the keys broke off. They were never found.

Jenny's father's name was Li. It's the most common name in China, or so I've heard. But when they moved to Canada, her mother wanted them to fit in.
> look at chalkboard

> look at chalkboard
Behind the podium is a chalkboard, messy with the half-erased traces of  music staffs and notes. In the bottom right corner, neatly written in dull orange chalk:

April 24, 2003
Mrs. Redford, Substitute Teacher

It's been seventeen years since she died. Seventeen years I've spent in this hellhole, where every second feels like an eternity. Seventeen years, the same amount of time that she was on this earth. And yet, what is time in the face of death?
