Storage Room

You are in a narrow walkway, hemmed in on both sides by shelves full of instruments. Every row is clearly labelled by sharpie on a piece of masking tape: heavy instruments like "Tuba" are put on the lower shelves and lighter ones like "Flute" are on the upper shelves. There is a small band office at the other end, but a drawn curtain prevents you from seeing inside. A  cabinet stands outside the office like a shabby sentry.

You can see a tuba, a trombone, a flute, a poster and a cabinet.
You can go west or east.
> look at cabinet

> look at cabinet
The cabinet is rusty but the keypad on it looks new. A piece of printed paper taped to it reads:

Please take instruments home at end of day. School not responsible for any lost or damaged property. If you have any information regarding the recent break-ins, please contact the Principal's Office immediately.

There is a keypad on the cabinet door.

Do I have to tell you again? Instrument practice is not allowed during recreational hour. That's what instrument practice hour is for.

This was one of Jenny's favorite places. She played the saxophone, and she was rather good at it too. She couldn't practice at home because of the neighbors, so Mr. Seymour gave her a key. She could come in and use this room whenever she wanted.
> use keypad

> use keypad
Enter combination
> 1953
You hear a beep and the cabinet pops open with a satisfying click. It's filled with tidy stacks of papers and binders, mostly class materials and grading sheets. The only thing that interests you is a backpack, built to look like a stuffed penguin. You pull it out, letting the cabinet slide shut on its own.
> open backpack

> open backpack
You open the backpack. Inside you find a water bottle, a school binder, a pencil case, and a small book bound in leather.
It contains a water bottle, a school binder, a pencil case and Angela's Journal.
> read journal

> read journal
The journal opens easily, its well worn bindings giving little resistance. A small green card drops out and you put it in your pocket. You flip to the latest page:

Friday April 4th

Today was the worst day of my life. I just found out that Jenny is planning a birthday party and I'm not invited. When she first arrived at Pickton Elementary, she was a pitiful thing: small, scrawny, unable to speak a word of English. I was the one who took her in, the only one who wanted to be her friend. For years we were inseparable, the only Asian students in a foreign land. And now, because puberty favored her and not me, she is popular and I am not. And she doesn't want anything to do with me.

All of the boys trip over themselves for Jenny. Nick, who I've had a crush on since 5th grade, asked her out within one month of knowing her. She draws them in with some sob story about her dad, some Chinese government official who went missing. I'm not saying it's not sad, just that she knows what she's doing.

Jenny has taken everything from me. I used to be Mr. Seymour's favorite student, his star musician. But ever since Jenny joined, things have been different. She's good, okay, but she's far from the best. How did it happen? How did she become the teacher's pet? It's so fucking obvious, the way she stays behind after class to chat with him, the way he always calls on her to demonstrate a new technique. Jazz band used to be my favorite class, now I can't even bear to show up, to be in the same room as her.

I hate Jenny. But I still wish that she would just talk to me, that she would invite me to her party . . .

Recreational hour has ended. Have your electronic devices ready for collection.

Time's up. I hope we can be more productive tomorrow. But then again, we've got all the time in the world.

