> look at desk

> look at desk
The desk is covered in so many layers of paper and junk that it is impossible to know what color the surface is. There are school notebooks, past SAT exams, university pamphlets, permission slips . . . your eye catches on a small leather book. You pull it out to find youself holding a journal identical to the one you found in the storage room cabinet. Tucked between the pages is a short letter without a signature, printed on thick paper with the corner ripped off:

Dear Jenny:
Only one more week until our reunion; I can hardly wait, after all these years. Remember, you cannot let your mother know. That is the most important thing. If she finds out, it will all be ruined. See you soon.

Hey! What do you think you're doing? You're supposed to be investigating her death, not putting your filthy fingers through her personal belongings! I will not stand by and let you disrespect her memory like this. You can come back when you learn how to behave.

Library

As far as public libraries go, this is a pretty nice one. A large, open space filled with reading desks, bean bags, and book stands is encircled by a maze of bookshelves. At one corner of the room is a small information desk. On the other side is a row of computer stations, with relatively new-looking monitors that speak of healthy public funding. To the north is a glass door leading to a smaller room. A shiny brass sign indicates that it was named after some rich guy: "Harvey S. Firestone Reading Room".

You can see a book stand, an information desk, a file cabinet and a computer station.
