Tuesday May 6

Mama has been so nosy as of late. She's always walking by, making sure that I'm doing my homework or working on practice SAT exams. If she catches me slacking, she will blow her top and lecture me for hours on the importance of studying and good work ethic. Does she realize that I could have done another two exams in the time she spent yelling at me? More often I find myself wishing I could have grown up with my father instead.

I've decided to hide the letters. With the big day coming up so soon, I can't afford to risk anything. She's always walking by and scanning over the things on my desk. I'll just have to put the letters somewhere she can't see. I mean, if I can't hide the letters OVER my desk . . .
> look under desk

> look under desk
You feel around under the table, and your hands find something strange. It's a bundle of letters, taped to the underside of the table.
> read bundle of letters

> read bundle of letters
The letters are neatly typed on thick printer paper, with a small logo of a heron on the top right corner. You pick out one at random:

Dearest Jenny:

All these years, I've never forgotten about you. I have a portrait of you from when you were three, and I keep it with me all the time. It's the one thing they haven't been able to take away from me. Through all these long years of imprisonment and torture, I've been kept alive by the thought that one day I will get to see my daughter again. And now that day is coming near.

Do you still have the saxphone that I gave you? I would love to hear you play it. Please bring it to our meeting.

Love,
Dad
