It's a black silk bag, sealed at the top with a drawstring. You open it and peer inside: a million stars twinkle at you from a silky void. You blink and look again. Inside is a set of small pearl buttons, like the kind you would find on a brass instrument.
> look at stack of letters

> look at stack of letters
The letters are neatly typed, sorted in order by date. You pick out one at random, a piece of thick printer paper with a small logo of a heron in one corner:

Dearest Jenny:

I'm sure you understand by now why your mother must not know. I believe that she feels guilty for having given up on me, having left me for dead. If she knew that I was still alive, she would be jealous of the father daughter bond that we share. She would want to keep you all to herself. We will tell her, but the time is not right. We must be patient.

Love,
Dad

I don't believe it.

Mrs. Vanderbilt, the librarian? She was the sweetest lady, middle aged and motherly. If this was a mystery story, she would be the least likely suspect.

The keys on the saxophone, Jenny's interest in the treasures of the Cultural Revolution . . . it all makes sense now. Her father wanted to smuggle the pearls out of the country by putting them on the saxophone. It was his last gift to her, and it was worth more than her and her mother could ever earn in a lifetime . . .

Jenny used to hang out at the library all the time. She must have left her journal here; Mrs. Vanderbilt must have read it and guessed the truth. She wrote those letters to Jenny, pretending to be her father, hiding it from her mother, arranging a nighttime meeting . . .

What a vile crime. To prey on the innocence and love of a child . . . I shudder to think of her thick arms, raising the saxophone high, bringing it down on Jenny, unsuspecting Jenny, my dear Jenny . . . What lent that terrible power to her arms? Was it greed? Was it hate? Hate for Jenny, or hate for herself? How can any sane person do such a vile and atrocious thing?

If I could only get my hands on her . . . alas, the justice system will have to serve. I hope they bring back the death penalty, I hope they put her in the chair, I hope she suffers. I hope she goes to Hell for all eternity. But even if she does, nothing will bring Jenny back . . . the sun has set, and it will never rise again.

Well, I'm off to have a conversation with my lawyer. I suspect she will want to hear what I have to say.

What's that? What about you? Well . . . you've done a good job, I suppose. But I don't have time to think about your reward right now. There are more important things at stake. We can talk again when I return.

